load libraries

library(sf)
library("rworldmap")
library(tidyverse)

load inputs

load("input_niche_tmp_analyses.rda")
map_world <- getMap(resolution = "high")
aus_map<-st_as_sf(map_world[which(map_world$ISO3=="AUS"),])

range maps phenotypes

## Nonmelanic range
# Convert nonmelanic_geoThin to sf object, set coordinates, and transform to appropriate CRS
nonmelanic_points <- st_as_sf(nonmelanic_geoThin, coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"), crs = 4326) %>% st_transform(3112)

# Create rangeMap for nonmelanic points: buffer, union, intersect with aus_map, and transform to desired CRS
rangeMap_nonmelanic <- st_buffer(nonmelanic_points, dist = 100000) %>%
  st_union() %>% 
  st_intersection(aus_map %>% st_transform(3112)) %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

## Melanic range
# Convert melanic_geoThin to sf object, set coordinates, and transform to appropriate CRS
melanic_points <- st_as_sf(melanic_geoThin, coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"), crs = 4326) %>% st_transform(3112)

# Create rangeMap for melanic points: buffer, union, intersect with aus_map, and transform to desired CRS
rangeMap_melanic <- st_buffer(melanic_points, dist = 100000) %>%
  st_union() %>% 
  st_intersection(aus_map %>% st_transform(3112)) %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

## Orange range
# Convert orange_geoThin to sf object, set coordinates, and transform to appropriate CRS
orange_points <- st_as_sf(orange_geoThin, coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"), crs = 4326) %>% st_transform(3112)

# Create rangeMap for orange points: buffer, union, intersect with aus_map, and transform to desired CRS
rangeMap_orange <- st_buffer(orange_points, dist = 100000) %>%
  st_union() %>% 
  st_intersection(aus_map %>% st_transform(3112)) %>% 
  st_transform(4326)

# Combine rangeMaps for all phenotypes into a single sf object and add phenotype labels
rangeMap_phenotypes <- st_sf(c(rangeMap_nonmelanic, rangeMap_melanic, rangeMap_orange)) %>%
            mutate(phenotype = c("nonmelanic", "melanic", "orange"))

Create ecoregion background

# Read the ecoregions shapefile
ecoregions <- st_read("Ecoregions2017.shp")
## Reading layer `Ecoregions2017' from data source 
##   `C:\Users\Fabian C. Salgado\Dropbox\PhD_FabianSalgado\research_proposal\aim2\climatic_layers\Ecoregions2017.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 847 features and 15 fields
## Geometry type: MULTIPOLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -180 ymin: -89.89197 xmax: 180 ymax: 83.62313
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
# Load the sf library for spatial operations
library(sf)

# Cast ecoregions to polygons and transform to the desired CRS (Coordinate Reference System)
cast_eco <- st_cast(ecoregions, "POLYGON") %>% st_transform(3112)

# Intersect phenotypes and ecoregions to identify overlapping areas
amix_ecoregions <- st_intersects(x = st_cast(ecoregions, "POLYGON") %>% st_transform(3112),
                                  y = rangeMap_phenotypes %>% st_transform(3112))
amix_ecoregions <- amix_ecoregions %>% as.data.frame() %>% distinct(`row.id`) %>% pull()

# Extract ecoregions intersecting with phenotypes based on the intersecting areas identified
amix_ecoregions <- cast_eco[amix_ecoregions,] %>% group_by(OBJECTID) %>% summarise()

# Identify regions intersecting with nonmelanic phenotypes
nonmelanic_regions <- st_intersects(amix_ecoregions, filter(.data = rangeMap_phenotypes %>% st_transform(3112),
                                                             phenotype == "nonmelanic")) %>% 
                      as.data.frame() %>% 
                      distinct(`row.id`) %>% 
                      pull()

# Identify regions intersecting with melanic phenotypes
melanic_regions <- st_intersects(amix_ecoregions, filter(.data = rangeMap_phenotypes %>% st_transform(3112),
                                                          phenotype == "melanic")) %>% 
                    as.data.frame() %>% 
                    distinct(`row.id`) %>% 
                    pull()

# Identify regions intersecting with orange phenotypes
orange_regions <- st_intersects(amix_ecoregions, filter(.data = rangeMap_phenotypes %>% st_transform(3112),
                                                          phenotype == "orange")) %>% 
                    as.data.frame() %>% 
                    distinct(`row.id`) %>% 
                    pull()

# Find intersections between different phenotype regions
non_melanic_inter <- intersect(nonmelanic_regions, melanic_regions)
intersect_all_morphs <- intersect(non_melanic_inter, orange_regions)

# Update ecoregions with phenotype information based on the intersections
amix_ecoregions <- amix_ecoregions %>% 
                      mutate(phenotype = case_when(row_number() %in% intersect_all_morphs ~ "all",
                                                   row_number() %in% intersect(nonmelanic_regions, melanic_regions) ~ "melanic_nonmelanic",
                                                   row_number() %in% intersect(nonmelanic_regions, orange_regions) ~ "orange_nonmelanic",
                                                   row_number() %in% intersect(melanic_regions, orange_regions) ~ "orange_melanic",
                                                   row_number() %in% melanic_regions ~ "melanic",
                                                   row_number() %in% orange_regions ~ "orange",
                                                   row_number() %in% nonmelanic_regions ~ "nonmelanic"))

# Transform ecoregions back to the original projection
amix_ecoregions <- amix_ecoregions %>% st_transform(4326)

Defining each color morphs modelling domain

The modeling area was characterized as the terrestrial ecoregions where species ranges overlap. Gathering environmental data from 10,000 points would provide an adequate sample size.

nonmelanic_c is the environment in sampled on occurrence points of the nonmelanic morph (Prob = 1) and on random background points (Prob = 0).

melanic_c is the environment in sampled on occurrence points of the nonmelanic morph (Prob = 1) and on random background points (Prob = 0).

orange_c is the environment in sampled on occurrence points of the nonmelanic morph (Prob = 1) and on random background points (Prob = 0).

library(terra)

chelsa_variables <- raster::stack(list.files(path = "chelsea", pattern = ".tif", full.names = TRUE))

# Extract variable names from file names
names_variables <- list.files(path = "chelsea", pattern = ".tif$", full.names = TRUE) %>% 
                    str_match(pattern = "\\w+.tif$") %>% 
                    gsub(pattern = ".tif", replacement = "") %>% 
                    as.vector()

# Assign descriptive names to the raster layers
names(chelsa_variables) <- paste0("chelsa_", names_variables)

Extract background points per morph

# Load the dismo package for species distribution modeling
library(dismo)

# Create a dataset for nonmelanic species
# Generate random background points within ecoregions intersecting with nonmelanic phenotypes
nonmelanic_bg <- randomPoints(mask(chelsa_variables[[1]], filter(.data = amix_ecoregions, phenotype %in% c("all", "melanic_nonmelanic", "nonmelanic", "orange_nonmelanic"))), n=10000)

# Combine coordinates of nonmelanic species occurrences with background points
nonmelanic_c <- rbind(mutate(nonmelanic_geoThin[, c("Longitude", "Latitude")], Prob = 1),
                      mutate(rename(data.frame(nonmelanic_bg), Longitude = x, Latitude = y), Prob = 0))

# Extract environmental variables for nonmelanic species occurrences and background points
nonmelanic_c <- cbind(nonmelanic_c, raster::extract(chelsa_variables, nonmelanic_c[, c("Longitude", "Latitude")])) %>%
                 na.omit()

# Create a dataset for melanic species
# Generate random background points within ecoregions intersecting with melanic phenotypes
melanic_bg <- randomPoints(mask(chelsa_variables[[1]], filter(.data = amix_ecoregions, phenotype %in% c("all", "melanic", "melanic_nonmelanic", "orange_melanic"))), 10000)

# Combine coordinates of melanic species occurrences with background points
melanic_c <- rbind(mutate(melanic_geoThin[, c("Longitude", "Latitude")], Prob = 1),
                   mutate(rename(data.frame(melanic_bg), Longitude = x, Latitude = y), Prob = 0))

# Extract environmental variables for melanic species occurrences and background points
melanic_c <- cbind(melanic_c, raster::extract(chelsa_variables, melanic_c[, c("Longitude", "Latitude")])) %>%
              na.omit()

# Create a dataset for orange phenotypes
# Generate random background points within ecoregions intersecting with orange phenotypes
orange_bg <- randomPoints(mask(chelsa_variables[[1]], filter(.data = amix_ecoregions, phenotype %in% c("all", "orange", "orange_nonmelanic", "orange_melanic"))), 10000)

# Combine coordinates of orange phenotype occurrences with background points
orange_c <- rbind(mutate(orange_geoThin[, c("Longitude", "Latitude")], Prob = 1),
                  mutate(rename(data.frame(orange_bg), Longitude = x, Latitude = y), Prob = 0))

# Extract environmental variables for orange phenotype occurrences and background points
orange_c <- cbind(orange_c, raster::extract(chelsa_variables, orange_c[, c("Longitude", "Latitude")])) %>%
            na.omit()

Univariate analysis of climat niche divergence

visualizing climatic niche shift along single environmental variables

Chelsa data

create data for plotting

plot_data <- mutate(nonmelanic_c,
                    morph = "nonmelanic") %>% 
  bind_rows(mutate(melanic_c,
                   morph = "melanic")) %>% 
  bind_rows(mutate(orange_c,
                   morph = "orange")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -c("Longitude","Latitude","Prob","morph"),names_to = "variable",values_to = "value") %>% 
  mutate(Prob = factor(Prob))
# Define colors for morphs
o_col <- "#e65d2f"  # Orange color
w_col<-"#AFA15A"     # White color
b_col <- "black"     # Black color

# Create a vector of colors
colours <- c(b_col, w_col, o_col)

# Plotting using ggplot
ggplot() +
  # Add density plot for 'Prob' equal to 1
  geom_density(data = filter(plot_data, Prob == "1"),
               aes(x = value, color = morph,fill=morph)) +
  
  # Facet wrapping by 'variable' with customized labels
  facet_wrap(vars(fct_relevel(variable)),
             scales = "free",
             labeller = as_labeller(c(
               "chelsa_cmi" = str_wrap("Climate moisture index [kg m-2 month-1]", width = 20),
               "chelsa_pet" = str_wrap("Potential evapotranspiration [kg m-2]", width = 20),
               "chelsa_pr" = str_wrap("ln Precipitation amount [kg m-2 month-1/100]", width = 20),
               "chelsa_rsds" = str_wrap("Surface downwelling shortwave flux in air [MJ m-2 d-1]", width = 20),
               "chelsa_tasmax" = str_wrap("Mean daily maximum 2m air temperature [K/10]", width = 20),
               "chelsa_tasmin" = str_wrap("Mean daily minimum 2m air temperature [K/10]", width = 20)))) +
  
  # Manually set color values and labels
  scale_color_manual(values = colours,labels = c("melanic", "nonmelanic morph", "orange")) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = alpha(colours,0.5),labels = c("melanic", "nonmelanic morph", "orange"))+
  
  # Customize theme
  theme_classic() +
    theme(
    title = element_text(size = 10),
    strip.background = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_text(size = 8),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    aspect.ratio = 1
  )

loadings<-amix_pca$co

squared_loadings <- loadings^2

# Calculate total variance explained by each principal component
total_variance <- apply(squared_loadings, 2, sum)

contribution_pca1<-(squared_loadings[,1]) / total_variance[1]

names(contribution_pca1)<-rownames(squared_loadings)

Climate nich divergence analysis under COUE (Centroid shift, Overlap, Unfilling and Expansion) framework with all the morphs.

Build the grids for each colour morph

library(ecospat)

amix_globclim <- amix_pca$li
colnames(amix_globclim)<-names(chelsa_variables)
#scores of presences
nonmelanic_p_li <- ade4::suprow(amix_pca,nonmelanic_c[nonmelanic_c$Prob==1,4:length(nonmelanic_c)])$li
melanic_p_li <- ade4::suprow(amix_pca,melanic_c[melanic_c$Prob==1,4:length(melanic_c)])$li
orange_p_li <- ade4::suprow(amix_pca,orange_c[orange_c$Prob==1,4:length(orange_c)])$li

#scores of whole area
nonmelanic_all_li<- ade4::suprow(amix_pca,nonmelanic_c[,4:length(nonmelanic_c)])$li
melanic_all_li<- ade4::suprow(amix_pca,melanic_c[,4:length(melanic_c)])$li
orange_all_li<- ade4::suprow(amix_pca,orange_c[,4:length(orange_c)])$li

#gridding
nonmelanic_grid <- ecospat.grid.clim.dyn(glob = amix_globclim[1:2], 
                                     glob1 = nonmelanic_all_li[1:2], 
                                     sp = nonmelanic_p_li[1:2], 
                                     R = 100, 
                                     th.sp = 0)
melanic_grid <- ecospat.grid.clim.dyn(glob = amix_globclim[1:2], 
                                    glob1 = melanic_all_li[1:2], 
                                     sp = melanic_p_li[1:2], 
                                     R = 100, 
                                     th.sp = 0)
orange_grid <- ecospat.grid.clim.dyn(glob = amix_globclim[1:2], 
                                     glob1 = orange_all_li[1:2], 
                                     sp = orange_p_li[1:2], 
                                     R = 100, 
                                     th.sp = 0)

Niche equivalency

Under niche conservatism Niche equivalency test H0: niche overlap is equivalent to the random distribution

Niche equivalency test H1: the observed overlap between A and B niche is higher than if the two niches are randomized

Under niche divergence Niche divergence test H0: niche overlap is equivalent to the random distribution

Niche divergence test H1: the observed overlap between A and B niche is lower than if the two niches are randomized

eq_test_divergence <- ecospat.niche.equivalency.test(nonmelanic_grid,melanic_grid,rep=1000,overlap.alternative="lower")

eq_test_conservatism <- ecospat.niche.equivalency.test(nonmelanic_grid,melanic_grid,rep=1000,overlap.alternative="higher")
ecospat.plot.overlap.test(eq_test_divergence, "D", "Equivalency")

ecospat.plot.overlap.test(eq_test_divergence, "I", "Equivalency")

ecospat.plot.overlap.test(eq_test_conservatism, "D", "Equivalency")

ecospat.plot.overlap.test(eq_test_conservatism, "I", "Equivalency")

Niche similarity test

Under niche conservatism Niche equivalency test H0: niche overlap is similar to the random distribution

Niche equivalency test H1: the observed overlap between A and B niche is higher than if the two niches are randomized

Under niche divergence Niche divergence test H0: niche overlap is similar to the random distribution

Niche divergence test H1: the observed overlap between A and B niche is lower than if the two niches are randomized

sim_test_1_cons <- ecospat.niche.similarity.test(nonmelanic_grid,
                                          melanic_grid, 
                                          rep=1000, 
                                          overlap.alternative = "higher", 
                                          rand.type=1)
sim_test_2_cons <- ecospat.niche.similarity.test(melanic_grid, 
                                            nonmelanic_grid,
                                          rep=1000, 
                                          overlap.alternative = "higher", 
                                          rand.type=1)
ecospat.plot.overlap.test(sim_test_1_cons, "D", "Similarity")
